  "response": "Magnesium is considered a solid under standard conditions of temperature and pressure (STP), which are 0 degrees Celsius (32 degrees Fahrenheit) and 1 atmosphere of pressure. At these conditions, magnesium exists as a shiny, silver-white metal with a crystalline structure. Its solid state is due to the strong metallic bonds between its atoms, which keep them in a fixed arrangement. If you heat magnesium to its melting point of about 650 degrees Celsius (1,202 degrees Fahrenheit), it will become a liquid. Further heating to around 1,091 degrees Celsius (1,996 degrees Fahrenheit) will cause magnesium to vaporize and become a gas. However, at room temperature, magnesium is a solid.",
